Subseries B: Inventory Cards: Works Sold

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content

Subseries comprises index cards created for each artwork sold by the gallery. Each card displays that artwork's inventory number and invoice number, which can also be found on corresponding records in this series. The cards are color coordinated.

Pink card: The work was given to Annina Nosei, that is, she did not buy it. There was no money involved. On many of these cards you will find written the word "gift."

Blue card: The work was bought by the Gallery. Most cards denote the amount paid.

White card: The work was consigned to the gallery either by the artist, another dealer, another gallery, or a collector.

Arrangement

Subseries is arranged in its original order. The index cards were originally contained in file drawers labeled "Works Sold" followed by an alphabetical range. This naming convention has been replicated here (e.g., the cards under the heading "Works Sold A-F" were originally held together in one file drawer labeled "Works Sold A-F"). The ranges of artists contained in each box has been provided by the archivist in the space below the box number.

Subseries C: Inventory Cards: Returned to Artist

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content

Subseries comprises index cards created for each artwork that the gallery attempted to sell but could not and returned to the artist. Each card displays that artwork's inventory number, which can also be found on corresponding records in this series. The cards are color coordinated.

Pink card: The work was given to Annina Nosei, that is, she did not buy it. There was no money involved. On many of these cards you will find written the word "gift."

Blue card: The work was bought by the Gallery. Most cards denote the amount paid.

White card: The work was consigned to the gallery either by the artist, another dealer, another gallery, or a collector.

Arrangement

Subseries is arranged in its original order. The index cards were originally contained in file drawers labeled "RTA" (which stands for "Returned to Artist") followed by an alphabetical range. This naming convention has been replicated here (e.g., the cards under the heading "RTA A-D-F" were originally held together in one file drawer labeled "RTA A-D-F"). The ranges of artists contained in each box has been provided by the archivist in the space below the box number.

Subseries D: Inventory Books

langmaterial

English

Arrangement

Subseries is arranged in numerical order by inventory number. Folders are labeled with the title on front of the original ledger.

Scope and Content

Series comprises ten twelve-column ledgers organized by the inventory number assigned to each artwork. Each entry in each ledger gives the inventory number, the artist's name, the work's title, the date the work was received by the gallery, the year the work was executed, the size of the work, the artist's price, the consignee, the work's medium, the gallery's suggested price, amount owed to the gallery, and the work's current location including to whom it sold or if it was returned to the artist.

Subseries E: Collector's Books

Scope and Content

According to the gallery, Collector's Books and Artist Books are different forms of the same function. At a cursory glance, Collector's Books comprises ledgers that seem to document what artist's work (by invoice number) was sold to what collector (whether individual or institution), while Artist Books comprises small spiral-bound notebooks listing the names, addresses, and phone numbers (sometimes in the form of business cards affixed to the pages) of persons and institutions interested in purchasing the work of certain artists. Often in Artist Books, a name and address will be accompanied by a note that reads "interested in 'X work of art'."

The ledger sheets in Collector's Book A-I and Collector's Book J-O are from National brand top-lock post binders. Collecto'rs Book P-Z is from a Six Star brand top-lock post binder.

Arrangement

Subseries is arranged in its original order. Ledger sheets were originally contained in large top-lock post binders and divided alphabetically by tabbed dividers. That arrangement has been replicated here at the folder level. The labels "Collector's Book A-I," "Collector's Book J-O," and "Collector's Book P-Z" were copied from labels on the binders themselves.

Subseries F: Artist Books

Scope and Content

According to the gallery, Collector's Books and Artist Books are different forms of the same function. At a cursory glance, Collector's Books comprises ledgers that seem to document what artist's work (by invoice number) was sold to what collector (whether individual or institution), while Artist Books comprises small spiral-bound notebooks listing the names, addresses, and phone numbers (sometimes in the form of business cards affixed to the pages) of persons and institutions interested in purchasing the work of certain artists. Often in Artist Books, a name and address will be accompanied by a note that reads "interested in 'X work of art'."

Arrangement

Subseries is arranged alphabetically by first artist's last name printed on the front of the book.

Subseries is arranged chronologically.

Scope and Content

The final folder in this series, ["Gallery Policies"], while not an invoice, was originally filed with the invoices, so has remained in this series.

Series III: Artist Files

Dates:
1963-2004

langmaterial

English

Scope and Content

Series comprises paper documents (including artists' bios, price lists, clippings, correspondence, exhibition announcements) and photographic materials relating to artists represented by the gallery and shows held at the gallery.

Subseries A: General Artist Files

Scope and Content

Subseries comprises files kept by Annina Nosei Gallery on artists both represented and not represented by the gallery. Materials include clippings, gallery-produced artist's biographies, photographs, correspondence, and exhibition announcements and other promotional material.

Arrangement

Folders in this subseries were stored in two different ways: the majority filed alphabetically in filing cabinets and the rest filed by artist in cardboard boxes and letter boxes. Since, according to Annina Nosei, the only reason for the different filing systems was lack of space in the filing cabinets, folders from boxes are interfiled alphabetically with the folders from the filing cabinets.

Subseries B: Master Slides Binders

Arrangement

This subseries originally consisted of four large binders labeled "Master Slides A-C," "Master Slides C-G," "Master Slides H-M," "Master Slides M-O," and "Master Slides P-Z." This original arrangement has been preserved while the slides were transferred to new, archivally sound sleeves and rehoused in acid-free binders. The material in the binders is divided by tabbed dividers arranged by artists' names.

Scope and Content

Subseries comprises master slides kept by the Annina Nosei Gallery.

Subseries C: Visuals Binders

langmaterial

English

Arrangement

This subseries originally comprised one binder per artist. This original arrangement has been preserved while the visual materials were transferred to new, archivally sound sleeves and rehoused in acid-free binders.

The original binder labels have been reproduced here, except for what appears between brackets ("[ ]"), such information was provided by the archivist for ease of use.

Some transparencies were originally sleeved in mylar, labeled, and placed in one of eight numbered pockets in a single mylar sleeve. For preservation reasons, the original sleeve was discarded. The transparencies are placed in archivally sound plastic sleeves, and a note is included that reproduces the original numbering, usually in the form, "From Binder Sleeve Pocket Numbered 'x.'"

Many of the original sleeves in the binders contained several [elements]. Each [element] has been separated out, placed in its own sleeve, and placed in a new binder following a cover sheet giving the original binder sleeve's order (e.g., Binder Sleeve 2/7), the series and subseries, and the name of the artist as it appeared on the original binder.
When an original sleeve or binder pocket contained a large majority of paper-based [elements], everything in that sleeve or pocket was removed and placed in a folder that can be found in ["Subseries D: Material Separated"].

If the original sleeve or pocket contained a large amount of photographic material as well as paper-based material, then the paper material is removed to a folder labelled with the binder's name followed by the phrase "From Binder Sleeve x/y," and the photographic material is resleeved and arranged as described above.
In some cases, a binder sleeve with four pockets will contain four or more 3"x5" transparencies in plastic sleeves with a card or sticker taped to the sleeve giving the piece's name and dimensions. Each individually sleeved transparency is taken out of its sleeve and placed in an archival three-pocket mylar sleeve. The original plastic sleeve, if it has bears notations, is placed in the same sleeve as the transparency, along with the card or sticker that bears infomation on the artwork pictured.

Scope and Content

Series comprises visual materials (photographic prints, transparencies, slides, negatives, etc.) and other promotional material (including artists' bios and price lists) accumulated by the Annina Nosei Gallery.

Subseries D: Material Separated from Master Slides Binders

Scope and Content

Series comprises mostly photographic prints and transparencies, with some slides, polaroids, and paper materials, used to inventory and promote works sold through Annina Nosei Gallery.

Arrangement

The order of folders in this subseries follows the order of binders in Series III, Subseries B. Artists' names in folder titles below that appear in brackets (e.g., "[From "Jose Bedia"]")were taken from the tabbed dividers that originally organized the material in the binders.

Subseries E: Material Separated from Visuals Binders

Scope and Content

Subseries comprises material separated from Series III, Subseries C, due to some aspect of the material that made it unsuitable to be placed in a binder.

Arrangement

The order of folders in this subseries follows the order of binders in Series III, Subseries C. Each folder represents one binder sleeve; for example, when all the material has been removed from the ninth sleeve of the "Pizzi Cannella" binder in Subseries C, it is placed in a folder, which is then labeled "Pizzi Cannella [Binder Sleeve 9/12]." When only some of the material is removed from a sleeve, it is noted in the folder title as "[From Binder Sleeve x]" (e.g., Pizzi Cannella [From Binder Sleeve 4/12]").

General Note

The folder labeled "[Izumi Chiaraluce Binder]" contains the entirety of the binder since it is mostly paper material.

Scope and Content

Series comprises Polaroid instant photographs from a box labeled "Polaroids."

Arrangement

Polaroid photographs were originally sorted with dividers. The original order has been maintained, including the dividers. The labels of the dividers have been preserved here. Where Polaroids from one artist were found under another artist's label, or when there are no labeled dividers (as in the beginning of Binder BC), the artist's name has been provided in brackets by the archivist to aid the researcher.

Series V: Exhibition Records

Dates:
1980-2009

Scope and Content

Series comprises materials related to each show held at the Annina Nosei Gallery. Materials include installation photographs, price lists, artist bios, exhibition cards, press clippings, catalogs, and guest books.

Arrangement

Exhibition Records: Subseries A-G comprise what the gallery termed "Exhibition Records," a term denoting all materials produced and collected in connection with a specific exhibition. These records were originally sleeved in binders. Material has been removed from binder sleeves and binders and placed in folders and boxes. Titles of binders have been retained in the titles of subseries.

Materials in these subseries are arranged in the order in which they were filed in their original binders, which is reverse chronological order for each binder. The binders (subseries) themselves have been ordered chronologically by the archivist.

Each folder represents a specific exhibition (e.g., all of the material relating to the Barbara Kruger March 5-26, 1983 show is put into one folder), regardless of how many binder sleeves the material orignally occupied. Most binders were accompanied by a list of binder contents listing the exhibitions included in the date range for that binder. These lists, where available, were used by the archivist to create folder titles. Where these lists were absent, the archivist has supplied folder titles by referring to the chronological lists found in the yearly catalogs for the gallery.

Some consecutive exhibitions are represented by very little material. In such a case, that material is placed in a single folder, which is labelled with the artists' names and show titles separated by semicolons (e.g., "[Stephen Mueller; Keith Milow; Group Show; Keith Haring]").

Catalogs: Subseries H comprises catalogs created by the gallery to accompany each exhibition.

Guest Books: Subseries I comprises guest books signed by gallery patrons.

Subseries H: Catalogs

Scope and Content

Subseries comprises catalogs of artists and artists' works produced regularly by the Annina Nosei Gallery. Catalogs come in the following categories: Individual Artists, "Group Shows," "7 Latin American Artists," "The Door," and Occasional Compilations of exhibitions over a span of three to five years, each of which is described as "a testimony recording a seletion of the artist I have worked with during the last three [or "five"] years."

Arrangement

Subseries is arranged chronologically by year and alphabetically within the same year.

Scope and Content

Before opening her own gallery, Annina Nosei curated exhibitions at various locations. Series comprises material drawn from the exhibitions "Discussions," "Painting," "Memory," "Angelo Savelli: Paintings & Sculpture," and comprises press releases, programs, brochures, artist bios, and an essay by Annina Nosei on Savelli.

langmaterial

English

Arrangement

Materials were originally grouped by artist and shelved in magazine files bearing the artist's name. That grouping is preserved, and the folder titles bear the original labels of the magazine files.

The folder "Jose Bedia [/Guillermo Kuitca]" contains material related to both Bedia and Kuitca though the original folder only listed Bedia's name.

Scope and Content

Series comprises some monographs of artists represented by the gallery, some periodicals that include artists represented by the gallery, and various clippings, all accumulated and stored by the gallery.
